@Node Requirements "AmTAGID3 / Requirements"

@{_Section "Requirements"}

  @{FG Highlight}@{B}AmTAGID3@{UB} requires :@{FG Text}

      Kickstart V39 (OS 3.x) or above.
      @{" Magic User Interface " Link MUI} V3.8 or above.
      @{" BetterString.mcc " link betterstring} V11.2 or above.

  @{FG Highlight}Install @{B}AmTAGID3@{UB} :@{FG Text}

      Anywhere in your path :)

  @{FG Highlight}MUI :@{FG Text}

      If you do not have @{U}MUI@{UU} you will have to download it from somewhere and
      install it. The latest version on Aminet is 3.8. @{U}MUI@{UU} is much too large
      to be included here.

@EndNode

@Node Usage "AmTAGID3 / Usage"

@{_Section "Usage"}

  @{b}AmTAGID3@{ub}

    @{" The command line " Link CmdLineArgs} @{_Contents "Giving arguments via the Shell"}
    @{" The famous GUI   " Link GUI} @{_Contents "Visual part of the iceberg."}

  The best usage is of course within a file manager like @{b}DOpus@{ub},  or  another
  one,  and  configure  a button with it. Here is a sample configuration for
  @{b}Directory Opus 5 Magellan@{ub} :


  Function : AmigaDOS   C:AmTAGID3 {o}

  Flags : CD Source
          Run asynchronously
          Do all files

  Look @{" here " link Cancel} for more info about using it within a file manager.

@EndNode

@Node CmdLineArgs "Command line arguments"

@{_Section "Command line arguments"}

  Pretty simple. As @{B}@{U}AmTAGID3@{UB}@{UU} uses the @{U}ReadArgs@{UU} function from the @{U}dos.library@{UU},
  the command line arguments are really easy to use and understand  both  for
  the user (you) and for the developper (me) ;-)

  The template is as follows :

  @{" MPEGFILE/A          " link MPEGFILE}
  @{" NQR=NOQUITREQUEST/S " link NOQUITREQUEST}
  @{" GL=GENRELINES/K/N   " link GENRELINES}
  @{" RS=REMSPACES/S      " link REMSPACES}
  @{" TN=TRACKNUMBER/S    " link TRACKNUMBER}
  @{" NOGUI/S             " link NOGUI}
  @{B}°@{UB} @{" NI=NOINFO/S         " link NOINFO}
  @{B}°@{UB} @{" NO=NOTAGS/S         " link NOTAGS}
  @{B}°@{UB} @{" LI=LINEINFO/S       " link LINEINFO}
  @{B}°@{UB} @{" AC=AMIGACOMMENT/S   " link AMIGACOMMENT}


  @{B}°@{UB} means that the specified command line switch only  make  sense  when  the
    option NOGUI is used.

  @{B}@{U}Note :@{UB}@{UU} Any error regarding the command line (ie: no filename supplied,  non
  existing file, etc...) generates an error message which is displayed on the
  default output (most of the time, the shell console)

@EndNode

@Node MPEGFILE "Command line arguments / MPEGFILE/A"

  @{FG Highlight}MPEGFILE/A@{FG Text} (ARGUMENT, mandatory entry)

    The name of the MPEG  Audio  file.  You  @{U}MUST@{UU}  enter  a  name,  otherwise
    @{B}AmTAGID3@{UB} won't run.

@EndNode

@Node NOQUITREQUEST "Command line arguments / NQR=NOQUITREQUEST/S"

  @{FG Highlight}NQR=NOQUITREQUEST/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

    This option makes @{B}AmTAGID3@{UB} react differently when  quitting.  By  default
    it asks you if you really want to quit. This requester avoid quitting the
    the program by accidentaly pressing ESC (which is the default  hotkey  to
    close @{U}MUI@{UU} windows). This option removes this safety requester in case  it
    bores you :)

    NQR is short for NOQUITREQUEST.

@EndNode

@Node GENRELINES "Command line arguments / GL=GENRELINES/K/N"

  @{FG Highlight}GL=GENRELINES/K/N@{FG Text} (KEYWORD, numeric, optional)

    This option lets you specify the number of visible lines  of  the  genre
    list.  There's no limit check for this option. If @{u}MUI@{uu} isn't able to open
    the list as big as you like with the list font, it'll fallback  to  tiny
    font  and then to @{u}Topaz8@{uu} @{u}ROM@{uu} font is it's still too big. Finally, if you
    have specified a too large amount of visible lines (ie: 150),  the  list
    won't open. Be aware of that :)

    GL is short for GENRELINES.

@EndNode

@Node REMSPACES "Command line arguments / RS=REMSPACES/S"

  @{FG Highlight}RS=REMSPACES/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

    This option is for crappy TAG ID3 editors like  @{b}MP3Info@{ub}  (@{b}UNIX@{ub}),  @{b}WinAmp@{ub}
    (@{b}Win95@{ub}/@{b}NT@{ub})  which fill up the empty parts of a field with SPACES instead
    of ZEROS (char '\0'). This option allows  you  to  remove  those  useless
    and ugly spaces.

    Before : Title "@{bg highlight}Some title                    @{bg back}"
    After  : Title "@{bg highlight}Some title@{bg back}"

    RS is short for REMSPACES.

@EndNode

@Node TRACKNUMBER "Command line arguments / TN=TRACKNUMBER/S"

  @{FG Highlight}TN=TRACKNUMBER/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

  Before anything, read @{" TAG ID3 " link TAGID3} section about restrictions.

  @{u}GUI@{uu}

    This option add a little slider  gadget  right  to  the  comment  string
    gadget.  Clicking on it allows you to set the Track Number of the CD the
    song was extracted from.

    Holding the mouse over it some time displays a  bubble  help  indicating
    the shorcut to access this gadget.


  @{u}Shell@{uu}

    This option allows you display the « Track » field is  present  in  case
    you use the @{" NOGUI " link NOGUI} option. The TAG ID3 part of the output looks
    like this :

Title   : Amiga forever
Artist  : Paula
Album   : Amiga is born
Year    : 1985
Genre   : Other
Track   : 1
Comment : In memory of Jay Miner

    If you don't  specify  the  option  TN=TRACKNUMBER/S  but  the   TAG ID3
    contains  info  about  it,  a  little note is added right to the COMMENT
    field of TAG ID3 if it exists so it looks like this:

Title   : Amiga forever
Artist  : Paula
Album   : Amiga is born
Year    : 1985
Genre   : Other
Comment : In memory of Jay Miner  (uses the « Track » field, value of « 1 »)


    TN is short for TRACKNUMBER.

@EndNode

@Node NOGUI "Command line arguments / NOGUI/S"

  @{FG Highlight}NOGUI/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

    This option allows you to NOT display the @{u}MUI@{uu} GUI and  no  @{u}MUI@{uu}  part  is
    loaded  when  this  option is specified. This option is useful for basic
    MPEG Audio database creation when @{b}AmTAGID3@{ub} is used in  conjunction  with
    directory  utilities  such  as @{u}List@{uu} or any other  tool  like  that  with
    LFORMAT capabilities.

    If you specify this option, then some of the following  options  may  be
    useful. They only make sense with this option activated, otherwise, they
    have no effect.

    @{" NI=NOINFO/S       " link NOINFO}
    @{" NO=NOTAGS/S       " link NOTAGS}
    @{" LI=LINEINFO/S     " link LINEINFO}
    @{" AC=AMIGACOMMENT/S " link AMIGACOMMENT}

    Specifying both NOINFO and NOTAGS is of little interest  as  nothing  is
    displayed to the output ;)

    Unless NOINFO and/or NOTAGS are specified, the default output is :

    @{u}Shell>@{uu} AmTAGID3 "Amiga forever.MP3" NOGUI
    Version   : MPEG-1
    Layer     : III
    Mode      : Joint-Stereo
    Bitrate   : 128Kbps
    Frequency : 44100Hz

    Title   : Amiga forever
    Artist  : Paula
    Album   : Amiga is born
    Year    : 1985
    Genre   : Other
    Comment : In memory of Jay Miner

@EndNode

@Node NOINFO "Command line arguments / NI=NOINFO/S"

  @{FG Highlight}NI=NOINFO/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

    This option prevents @{b}AmTAGID3@{ub} from displaying infos about the MPEG Audio
    file so the output only looks like this :

    @{u}Shell>@{uu} AmTAGID3 "Amiga forever.MP3" NOGUI NOINFO
    Title   : Amiga forever
    Artist  : Paula
    Album   : Amiga is born
    Year    : 1985
    Genre   : Other
    Comment : In memory of Jay Miner


    NI is short for NOINFO.
@EndNode

@Node NOTAGS "Command line arguments / NT=NOTAGS/S"

  @{FG Highlight}NT=NOTAGS/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

    This option prevents @{b}AmTAGID3@{ub} from displaying the TAG ID3 from the  MPEG
    Audio files file so the output only looks like this :

    @{u}Shell>@{uu} AmTAGID3 "Amiga forever.MP3" NOGUI NOTAGS
    Version   : MPEG-1
    Layer     : III
    Mode      : Joint-Stereo
    Bitrate   : 128Kbps
    Frequency : 44100Hz


    NT is short for NOTAGS.
@EndNode

@Node LINEINFO "Command line arguments / LI=LINEINFO/S"

  @{FG Highlight}LI=LINEINFO/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

    This option gives an alternative way of displaying info about  the  MPEG
    Audio file. It is displayed in one line and the output looks like this:

    @{u}Shell>@{uu} AmTAGID3 "Amiga forever.MP3" NOGUI LINEINFO
    MPEG-1 Layer III Joint-Stereo 128Kbps 44100Hz

    Title   : Amiga forever
    Artist  : Paula
    Album   : Amiga is born
    Year    : 1985
    Genre   : Other
    Comment : In memory of Jay Miner


    LI is short for LINEINFO.
@EndNode

@Node AMIGACOMMENT "Command line arguments / AC=AMIGACOMMENT/S"

  @{FG Highlight}AC=AMIGACOMMENT/S@{FG Text} (SWITCH, optional)

    This option allows you to output the @{u}AmigaDOS@{uu} comment field if there  is
    one  after  the  MPEG  Audio  infos  and the TAD ID3. It looks like this
    (provided you have set the AmigaDOS comment field the way it appears :)

    @{u}Shell>@{uu} AmTAGID3 "Amiga forever.MP3" NOGUI AMIGACOMMENT
    Version   : MPEG-1
    Layer     : III
    Mode      : Joint-Stereo
    Bitrate   : 128Kbps
    Frequency : 44100Hz

    Title   : Amiga forever
    Artist  : Paula
    Album   : Amiga is born
    Year    : 1985
    Genre   : Other
    Comment : In memory of Jay Miner

    [ 3:18 ] by Paula. Album « Amiga is born » (In memory of Jay Miner)


    AC is short for AMIGACOMMENT.
@EndNode


@Node GUI "The user interface"

@{_Section "The user interface"}

                                   @{" Menus " link Menus }

                @{FG Highlight}------------------@{FG Text} MP3 file @{FG Highlight}-----------------@{FG Text}
                @{"          Amiga forever.MP3           " link MP3File}@{" 3:10 " link MP3Duration}
                @{FG Highlight}------------------@{FG Text} TAG ID3 @{FG Highlight}------------------@{FG Text}
                  Title @{"Amiga forever                       " link MP3Title}
                 Artist @{"Paula                               " link MP3Artist}
                  Album @{"Amiga is born                       " link MP3Album}
                   Year @{" 1985 " link MP3Year}   Genre @{"      Other      " link MP3GenreText}@{" P " link MP3GenrePopup}
                Comment @{"In memory of Jay Miner           " link MP3Comment}@{" 1 " link TRACKNUMBER}
                @{FG Highlight}--------------@{FG Text} AmigaDOS comment @{FG Highlight}-------------@{FG Text}
                @{"[ 3:18 ] by Paula. Album « Amiga is born" link ADOSComment}@{" P " link MP3ADOSComList}
                @{FG Highlight}---------------------------------------------@{FG Text}
                @{"       TAG ID3 successfully loaded...       " link StatusText}
                @{FG Highlight}-----------------@{FG Text} Controls @{FG Highlight}------------------@{FG Text}
                @{"   Okay   " link Okay} @{"  Write   " link Write} @{"  Wipe... " link Wipe} @{"  Cancel  " link Cancel}


  @{B}@{U}Note :@{UB}@{UU} Pressing @{i}ESC @{ui}(@{u}MUI@{uu} default key to close windows)  or  selecting  the
  menu  item  «  @{u}QUIT@{uu} » exits @{b}AmTAGID3@{ub} without warning you about writing the
  TAG ID3 in case you have modified some fields. The only warning you get is
  the   "Are   you   sure  to  quit  ?"  in  case  you  have  not  used  the
  NQR=NOQUITREQUEST/S in the command line arguments.

  @{B}@{U}Note :@{UB}@{UU} Any error regarding the user  interface  (ie:  couldn't  write  the
  TAGID3,  couldn't  read, wipe, etc...) generates an error message which is
  displayed on a @{U}MUI@{UU} requester.
@EndNode

